  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The vendors who achieve the best results in Brisbane's inner east are rarely the ones who decided to sell in January and were on the market by February. They are the ones who made the decision six months earlier, spent that time on focused preparation, and launched when the property was genuinely ready. If you are reading this in late 2026 and thinking about selling in 2027, that is a useful window. Here is how to use it.</p>

      <p>The most important first step is to work backwards from a target settlement date rather than a target listing date. Settlement typically falls four to six weeks after signing a contract in Queensland. The campaign itself, from listing to contract, runs anywhere from two weeks for a strong auction campaign to six or eight weeks for private treaty. Factor in two to four weeks of pre-launch preparation after the property is ready, plus your preparation and repair work before that. A target settlement date of May 2027 implies you should be starting preparation work in earnest now.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why January and February are underrated preparation months</h2>
      <p>Most Brisbane homeowners assume that selling in autumn means listing in March. That is partially right, but the sellers who do best in March and April typically started their preparation in January. January and February in Brisbane's inner east are quieter market months: open home attendance drops slightly, and the most price-sensitive buyers are less active. But the buyers who are active during those months are typically serious, and there is less competing stock. A well-prepared property launched in late January can attract genuine competition from buyers who have been watching since before Christmas.</p>

      <p>More importantly, January and February are excellent months to get trades done. Plumbers, painters, and landscapers are often more available after the holiday rush, quotes are easier to get, and lead times are shorter than in the busy October to November window. If you have known maintenance items to address before listing, doing them in January rather than October gives you a better chance of getting the work done at reasonable cost and on your schedule rather than the tradie's.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The 6-week pre-launch checklist</h2>
      <p>Six weeks before you want to list is when the practical work intensifies. By this point, any significant repairs or renovations should already be done. The six-week window is for the finishing work: repainting scuffed walls and high-traffic areas, refreshing gardens and front fencing, addressing any drainage or damp issues, and booking your stylist if you are using one. This is also when you should be finalising your agent choice if you have not already, so the marketing plan and photography can be scheduled to coincide with your target launch date.</p>

      <p>Photography and video should be booked four to five weeks before you want to go live, with the actual shoot happening once all presentation work is complete. Rushing photography because the property is not quite ready is one of the most common and costly mistakes Brisbane vendors make. The listing photos are typically the first and sometimes only impression a buyer gets before deciding whether to attend an open home. A property that is 95% ready but photographed before the garden has been done will underperform compared to the same property photographed a week later when it is fully prepared.</p>

      <p>Your solicitor should be instructed to prepare the contract and gather the required documentation around the same time. In Queensland, the contract of sale requires a title search, a sustainability declaration, body corporate records (if applicable), and pool safety compliance certificates if you have a pool. These take time to compile and review. Starting this process four to five weeks before your intended launch date gives your solicitor adequate time without rushing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Matching your launch to Brisbane's seasonal buyer activity</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's inner-east property market has a reasonably consistent seasonal rhythm. Buyer activity and open home attendance tend to peak in March and April, ease off through June, recover slightly in August and September, and peak again in October. The post-Christmas period from late January through February is lower volume but genuinely active, and competition is often lower. The quiet periods are typically mid-December through mid-January, mid-winter (June to July), and the weeks immediately before and after Queensland school holidays.</p>

      <p>For most well-presented properties in the Bulimba corridor, Camp Hill, and the inner east generally, a launch date in late February or early March aligns well with buyer activity, buyer confidence after rate decisions, and low competing stock. A launch in late September or October is also strong but competes with more listings. The sweet spot for many vendors is not the obvious peak months but the period just before the peak, when buyer demand is building and stock levels are still relatively low.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do in December if you are planning an autumn 2027 sale</h2>
      <p>If you are in December 2026 and targeting an autumn 2027 sale, this month is for decisions and planning rather than action. Walk through your property with fresh eyes, or ask a trusted friend to do it, and make a list of every maintenance item, presentation issue, or functional shortcoming you have been tolerating. Be honest about the list. These are exactly the items buyers will notice and use to negotiate. Categorise them into: must fix before listing, worth fixing, and not worth addressing.</p>

      <p>Book your agent appraisal in January so you have a realistic price guide to inform your decisions. Brief your solicitor so they know a sale is coming and can start preparing documentation early. If you are planning significant repairs or a kitchen or bathroom refresh, get quotes in January so you can make decisions with full cost information rather than estimates. Identify a property stylist you would like to use and check their availability for your target styling date, which is typically two to three weeks before photography.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions to answer before committing to a campaign start date</h2>
      <p>Before you lock in a launch date with your agent, work through a short set of practical questions. Is every significant repair and presentation item you identified either completed or scheduled with a confirmed completion date before photography? Has your solicitor confirmed they can have the contract ready in time? If you need to sell before you can commit to a purchase, have you worked through the implications of bridging finance or a shorter settlement period?</p>

      <p>Are you genuinely prepared for the campaign demands? A well-run selling campaign requires the property to be available for open homes and private inspections, sometimes at short notice. The home needs to be in showing condition at all times, which is manageable but requires planning if you have young children, pets, or a busy schedule. Vendors who are mentally and practically prepared for the campaign demands consistently get better results than those who treat it as something that just happens around them.</p>

      <p>Finally, have an honest conversation with your agent about your expectations versus recent comparable evidence. If there is a gap between what you hope to achieve and what recent sales suggest, that conversation is worth having before the campaign starts rather than after the first offer comes in.</p>

